<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-935-848  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 935 848.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Dec 4 1989 v10 n48 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Antipiracy efforts are increasingly effective.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Scott, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A move by the Software Publisher's Association to pinpointcompanies who illegally copy software is paying dividends.andP;  Ahotline run by the organization is receiving calls from employeesand ex-employees of suspected pirates.andP;  Once such activity isindicated, an investigation of the charge is launched.andP;  Violatorsmay face a lawsuit with penalties that can mount up to $50,000 perinstance of copied software.andP;  A compromise effort has also beenestablished, where the violator agrees to an audit of thecompany's software.andP;  For each illegal copy found, the companyagrees to pay the full retail price, as well as paying to replaceeach illegal copy with a legal copy.andP;  Other sanctions to thwartthe piracy movement include an amnesty movement where illegalusers turn in their pirated copies for registered ones.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CopyrightCopyingComputer CrimesImpact AnalysisCompaniesSoftware Publishers Association.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>